      "title": "[Boing Boing] Wearable tails help elderly folks keep their balance",
      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/arque1-1.jpeg?fit=500%2C333&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/04/30/wearable-tails-help-elderly-folks-keep-their-balance.html\" rel=\"nofollow\" title=\"Wearable tails help elderly folks keep their balance\"><img alt=\"The Arque tail, from 2019\" class=\"webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image\" height=\"333\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/boingboing.net/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/arque1-1.jpeg?fit=500%2C333&amp;quality=60&amp;ssl=1\" style=\"display: block; margin: auto; margin-bottom: 5px;\" width=\"500\" /></a><p>About 25 million years after our ancestors traded theirs for an upright stance, a research team at Keio University Graduate School of Media Design gave our long-lost tails a comeback tour. The prototype, dubbed Arque, <a href=\"https://www.kmd.keio.ac.jp/realprojects/arque/\">was a meter-long wearable robot designed to help elderly users with balance problems</a>. &#8212; <a class=\"read-more\" href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/04/30/wearable-tails-help-elderly-folks-keep-their-balance.html\">Read the rest </a></p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://boingboing.net/2026/04/30/wearable-tails-help-elderly-folks-keep-their-balance.html\">Wearable tails help elderly folks keep their balance</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://boingboing.net\">Boing Boing</a>.</p>",
